'''Olexander Abramovytsch Beyderman''' ([[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]] {{lang|uk|Олександр Абрамович Бейдерман}}, [[Scientific transliteration]] ''{{lang|uk-Latn|Oleksandr Abramovyč Bejderman}}''; also: Bejderman ; * 1949 in [[Odessa]]) is a [[USSR|Soviet]]-[[Ukraine|Ukrainian]] writer<ref name="Schmalzl1998">{{cite book|last=Schmalzl|first=Christian|title=Odessa: Kapitel aus der Kulturgeschichte|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nj0_AQAAIAAJ|accessdate=6 April 2011|year=1998|publisher=Lassleben|language=German|pages=139–143}}</ref> of [[Jew]]ish descent. He is a lecturer of [[Hebrew]], [[Russian language|Russian]] and English philology at the University of [[Odessa]].

Beyderman writes in [[Yiddish language]], Ukrainian and [[Russian language|Russian]] and is considered to be simultaneously one of the last and more important Yiddish authors in the former areas of Russian Jews. His entree to Soviet literature took place with the assistance of literature functionaries of the time, though he was never an orthodox follower of the [[Socialist realism|dogmas of socialist realism]] and soon found his own style  combining realistic language with harsh expressiveness that outreaches the simplicity of his themes. He treats the [[Holocaust|Extermination of Jews]] in [[World War II]] as well as topics reminiscent of [[Sholem Aleichem]] and other earlier Jewish writers. His depictions range from subtle criticism of society to quasi-blasphemous [[sarcasm]]. His generation is probably the last one to use Yiddish as a literary language. His texts are read in Israel and the United States as well as in [[Ukraine]]. The editions of his novels and plays are more numerous in Russian and Ukrainian. During the last couple of years, Ukrainian has come to play a greater role in his writings.

Beyderman was a Fellow in the [[Moses Mendelssohn|Moses Mendelssohn Centre]] and works for the [[Claims Conference]].

