{{Infobox language |name=Shabaki |nativename=شەبەکی |states=[[Iraq]] |region= [[Mosul]] |speakers=250,000 |familycolor=Indo-European |fam2=[[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian]] |fam3=[[Iranian languages|Iranian]] |fam4=[[Western Iranian languages|Western]] |fam5=[[Northwestern Iranian languages|Northwestern I]] |fam6=[[Zaza–Gorani languages|Zaza–Gorani]]<ref name=":0"/><ref name=":1"/> |iso3=sdb |glotto=shab1251 |glottorefname=Shabak }} '''Shabaki''' is an [[Indo-Iranian languages|Indo-Iranian language]] and belongs to the subgroup [[Zaza–Gorani languages|Zaza-Gorani]]<ref name=":0">{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/subgroups/zaza-gorani|title=Zaza-Gorani|work=Ethnologue|access-date=2018-10-22|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=AZGUEQmFqfMC&pg=PA564&lpg=PA564&dq=zaza+gorani+shabak+language&source=bl&ots=Rp5HArGnWg&sig=_Qvw1GvO75a5Nb8LOHardxBu-zk&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjtyrzi_ZreAhXL2KQKHVtMCIk4ChDoATABegQICBAB#v=onepage&q=zaza%20gorani%20shabak%20language&f=false|title=A Survey of Word Accentual Patterns in the Languages of the World|last=Hulst|first=Harry van der|last2=Goedemans|first2=Rob|last3=Zanten|first3=Ellen van|date=2010|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=9783110196313|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=pGClDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA375&lpg=PA375&dq=zaza+gorani+shabaki&source=bl&ots=clA5PvI1AX&sig=842QvzReeCseJK-Yvfn9PO_DRFA&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjdy8zYtpreAhVrIcAKHZBpDzY4ChDoATABegQIBRAB#v=onepage&q=zaza%20gorani%20shabaki&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of Stateless Nations: Ethnic and National Groups around the World, 2nd Edition: Ethnic and National Groups around the World|last=Minahan|first=James B.|date=2016-08-01|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=9781610699549|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=YCEXDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA40&dq=shabaki+language&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjkgb6VqZjeAhXRtIsKHazcCKQQ6AEIRDAG#v=onepage&q=shabaki%20language&f=false|title=From Baghdad on the Tigris to Baghdad on the Subway|last=Hindo|first=Walid A.|date=2016-09-08|publisher=Archway Publishing|isbn=9781480834033|language=en}}</ref><ref name=":2">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=i7hJDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA287&dq=shabaki+language&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjkgb6VqZjeAhXRtIsKHazcCKQQ6AEIPjAF#v=onepage&q=shabaki%20language&f=false|title=Historical Dictionary of the Kurds|last=Gunter|first=Michael M.|date=2018-02-20|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9781538110508|language=en}}</ref> of the [[Western Iranian languages|Northwestern Iranian languages]]. The Shabaki language is spoken by the [[Shabak people]]<ref>Abd al-Jabbar, Falih. Ayatollahs, sufis and ideologues: state, religion, and social movements in Iraq. University of Virginia 2008.</ref><ref>Sykes, Mark. The Caliphs' last heritage: a short history of the Turkish Empire</ref> in the [[Mosul]] region of northern [[Iraq]]. It has similarities with the Northwestern Iranian language [[Gorani language|Gorani]] (or Hawrami), which is often referred as a "[[Kurdish languages|Kurdish]] dialect", although the Kurdish languages form an independent group within the Northwestern Iranian languages. Shabaki is a distinct language.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=QLPnBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT107&dq=schabaki+sprache&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwixr__LpJjeAhVJqIsKHYscBawQ6AEIKjAB#v=onepage&q=schabaki%20sprache&f=false|title=Die Stunde der Kurden: Wie sie den Nahen Osten verändern|last=Löwer|first=Hans-Joachim|date=2015-02-16|publisher=Styriabooks|isbn=9783990403549|language=de}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=-9RNCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA16&lpg=PA16&dq=shabake+language&source=bl&ots=gD7ywrrve2&sig=UqmuH710QDWEEwqId3G94Dr4dyo&hl=de&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwitkMryopjeAhUqAsAKHZOBBRkQ6AEwDnoECAcQAQ#v=onepage&q=shabake%20language&f=false|title=Iraq: The ancient sites and Iraqi Kurdistan|last=Hann|first=Geoff|last2=Dabrowska|first2=Karen|last3=Townsend-Greaves|first3=Tina|date=2015-08-07|publisher=Bradt Travel Guides|isbn=9781841624884|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-middle-east-28351073|title=Iraq: The minorities of Nineveh|last=al-Lami|first=Mina|date=2014-07-21|work=BBC News|access-date=2018-10-25|language=en-GB}}</ref> It also has elements of [[Arabic]], [[Turkish language|Turkish]] and [[Persian language|Persian]] language.<ref name=":2" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://minorityrights.org/minorities/shabak/|title=Shabak - Minority Rights Group|work=Minority Rights Group|access-date=2018-10-22|language=en-GB}}</ref> The number of speakers of Shabaki was estimated in 1989 to be between 10,000 and 20,000.<ref name="Ethnologue">[http://www.ethnologue.com/show_language.asp?code=sdb Ethnologue about Shabaki]</ref><ref name=Omniglot>[http://www.omniglot.com/writing/shabaki.php Omniglot Shabaki page]</ref> Currently, the number of native speakers of Shabaki is estimated at 250,000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://minorityrights.org/minorities/shabak/|title=Shabak - Minority Rights Group|work=Minority Rights Group|access-date=2018-10-27|language=en-GB}}</ref> [[File:Iranian Family Tree v2.0.png|thumb|[[Iranian languages]] family tree]] As Shabaki is one of the [[Zaza–Gorani languages]], it is most similar to languages like [[Gorani language|Gorani]] (Hewrami), [[Bajelani language|Bajelani]], [[Sarli language|Sarli]] and [[Zaza language|Zazaki]]. Because Zaza–Gorani belongs to the [[Northwestern Iranian languages|Northwestern Iranian branch]].
Shabaki is a language in its own right and not a spoken dialect of any other language, with its own vocabulary and pronunciations, despite the fact that words from many other languages have entered into it as a result of the geographical nearness to other ethnic tribes.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.niqash.org/en/articles/society/1862/|title=The Shabak - A Brief Overview|last=Glenewinkel|first=Klaas|work=Niqash|access-date=2018-10-26|language=en}}</ref>
